          "text": "NATIONAL CYBER SECURITY CENTRE\nTLP:AMBER — FOR NAMED RECIPIENTS ONLY\nAttribution Brief — Albion Energy Storage Incident\n\nCLASSIFICATION: The Albion Battery Hall incident has characteristics consistent with advanced persistent threat (APT) tradecraft. However, attribution to a specific nation-state actor is not confirmed at this time.\n\nKEY FINDINGS:\n1. Initial access vector (printer firmware supply chain) is consistent with techniques documented in NCSC advisory AA23-131A.\n2. The C2 infrastructure uses overlapping IP ranges previously associated with criminal ransomware groups and state-adjacent actors.\n3. The objective — disabling safety systems rather than encrypting for ransom — is atypical for financially-motivated actors and more consistent with disruptive/destructive goals.\n4. No ransom demand was made. This is unusual and significant.\n\nWAR EXCLUSION ANALYSIS (Section 5.4, LMA5567A):\nThe 'peacetime operations' threshold requires 'major detrimental impact on state functioning.' The Albion incident caused localised industrial disruption — significant, but below the threshold for invoking the war exclusion with confidence.\nNCSSC assessment: invoking the exclusion based on current evidence would be premature and legally contestable. Attribution is not sufficiently confirmed.\n\nDISCLOSURE RECOMMENDATION:\nFull disclosure of technical indicators (IOCs, C2 infrastructure, malware signatures) to the wider sector is recommended. Sharing under the NCSC information sharing framework will support detection and prevention at other critical national infrastructure sites.\n\nRef: NCSC-INC-2024-ALBE — Contact: r.ngata@ncsc.gov.uk",
